author: Lincoln de Sousa
commit_message:
Improving the stability of overriding existent attributes

Methods/classmethods/staticmethods created in the C-Land have different free()
functions from the same versions created from the Python-Land.

So, this commit is an attempt to skip the hassle of messing up with the `base`
free and inject custom code. Here we are just moving the old object to a `_c_`
prefixed attribute.

author: Lincoln de Sousa
commit_message:
Adding a C class stub to be used while writing tests

I was using python lists, strings and other core types while writing
tests. I got bizarre results while trying to mess with methods of core
python objects, like `list.append` and `str.lower`.

First, I will probably write documentation describing these experiences
and probably, for now, resigning to support such operations.

author: Lincoln de Sousa
commit_message:
Add the `curses` decorator

Just a shortcut to add a method to a built-in class:

    >>> @curses(dict, 'banner')
    ... def dict_banner(self):
    ...     l = len(self)
    ...     print('This dict has {0} element{1}'.format(
    ...         l, l is 1 and '' or 's')
    >>> {'a': 1, 'b': 2}.banner()
    'This dict has 2 elements'

author: Lukas Graf
commit_message:
Fix usage of dir() without arg to inspect local scope:

A call to dir() without arguments is supposed to list the names in the
local scope. Because forbiddenfruit monkey patches __buitin__.dir with
its own __filtered_dir__, an additional frame is present in the call
stack, making CPythons _dir_locals_ access the wrong frame.

This change makes __filtered_dir__ account for that and return
the names from the local scope of the actual calling frame.
